Research Question and Hypotheses

RQ: According to critics, what makes a good vampire movie? What words are commonly used to describe positively-reviewed vampire movies?

H1: Some words that are used to positively describe any movie (such as âgood,â âamazing,â and âfantasticâ) will be used to describe well-received vampire movies.

H2: Other words that may not typically describe positive reactions to movies in general (such as âbloody,â âgruesome,â and âdisturbingâ) may also be used to describe well-received vampire movies.

Loading and Cleaning Data

On Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/stefanoleone992/rotten-tomatoes-movies-and-critic-reviews-dataset/data), I found a dataset consisting of over 1 million reviews of over 17,000 movies from critics on Rotten Tomatoes. The data was scraped from the Rotten Tomatoes website on October 31, 2020, and thus only contains information about movies released in 2020 or earlier.

# contains all 1,000,000 reviews
all_reviews <- read.csv("C://Users/maura/Documents/DACSS/758/Final/rotten_tomatoes_critic_reviews.csv")

After cross-referencing the list of movies reviewed by critics in this dataset with a list of vampire movies, I narrowed down a final list of 154 vampire movie titles contained in the dataset.

Exploratory Data Analysis

After the reviews had been cleaned, I split them into two subsets: one consisting only of âFreshâ reviews (if the critic liked the movie), and one consisting only of âRottenâ reviews (if the critic didnât like the movie). There was an almost equal number of Fresh (4,181) and Rotten (4,073) reviews.

Word Clouds

Next, I wanted to get a sense of which words were most frequently used in both corpora.

# tokenize; remove punctuation, numbers, and stopwords
fresh_tokens <- tokens(fresh_corpus, 
                       remove_punct = T, remove_numbers = T) |>
  tokens_select(pattern=c("film", "films", "movie", "movies", 
                          "vampire", "vampires", "one", "two",
                          "like", "just", "still", "much", "even"), 
                select = "remove")

# make document feature matrix
fresh_dfm <- dfm(fresh_tokens) |>
  dfm_remove(stopwords('english')) |>
  dfm_trim(min_termfreq = 50, verbose = FALSE)

# make word cloud
set.seed(12)
textplot_wordcloud(fresh_dfm, color="darkgreen")
# tokenize; remove punctuation, numbers, and stopwords
rotten_tokens <- tokens(rotten_corpus, 
                       remove_punct = T, remove_numbers = T) |>
  tokens_select(pattern=c("film", "films", "movie", "movies", 
                          "vampire", "vampires", "one", "two",
                          "like", "just", "still", "much", "even"), 
                select = "remove")

# make document feature matrix
rotten_dfm <- dfm(rotten_tokens) |>
  dfm_remove(stopwords('english')) |>
  dfm_trim(min_termfreq = 50, verbose = FALSE)

# make word cloud
set.seed(12)
textplot_wordcloud(rotten_dfm, color="red")

The word clouds for the positive and negatively reviewed vampire movies have some overlap, but they also have their differences. The Fresh word cloud has words like âgood,â âgreat,â âbest,â âfun,â âoriginal,â âlove,â and âentertaining,â which are expected to be associated with positive reviews. The Rotten word cloud has words like âbad,â âenough,â âlittle,â ânever,â âworst,â ânothing,â and âmess,â which are expected to be associated with negative reviews. However, the Rotten word cloud also contains the common positive words like âgood,â âgreat,â âbest,â âfun,â âoriginal,â and âlove,â which might be frequently negated in the negative reviews, but that isnât captured by the unigram analysis performed here.

Both word clouds also contain some words related to specific movies, such as âTwilight,â âUnderworld,â âDracula,â âBlade,â and âBella.â Itâs not surprising that the vampire movie franchises with multiple entries like Twilight (5 films), Underworld (5 films), and Blade (3 films) are discussed more than films which stand alone. The character of Dracula is also featured in many different vampire movies, and even if he isnât explicitly present in them, he presents a well-known figure for critics to compare the depictions of other vampires to in their reviews. Other vampire-specific words in the clouds include âhorror,â âaction,â âblood,â âdark,â âshadows,â âgothic,â and âscary.â

Finally, both word clouds feature words pertaining to aspects of the movies that critics discuss. These words include âstory,â âplot,â âcharacters,â âgenre,â âeffects,â âscript,â âdirector,â and âperformance.â Going forward, it could be helpful to study how these elements of the movies are discussed (such as which adjectives frequently accompany them) to distinguish positive from negative reviews. A similar tactic could also be applied to the adjectives used near common words like âfilm,â âmovie,â or âvampire.â

# make a corpus with 2 documents (1 for all fresh and 1 for all rotten reviews)
fresh_review_text <- paste(fresh_reviews$review_content, collapse=" ")
rotten_review_text <- paste(rotten_reviews$review_content, collapse=" ")
fr_df <- tibble(freshness = c("Fresh", "Rotten"),
                review_text = c(fresh_review_text, rotten_review_text))
fr_corpus <- corpus(fr_df, docid_field = "freshness", text_field = "review_text")

# tokenize; remove punctuation, numbers, and stopwords
fr_tokens <- tokens(fr_corpus, remove_punct = T, remove_numbers = T) |>
  tokens_select(pattern="vampire", select = "remove")

# make document feature matrix
fr_dfm <- dfm(fr_tokens) |> dfm_remove(stopwords('english')) |>
  dfm_trim(min_termfreq = 100, verbose = FALSE)

# make comparison word cloud
set.seed(15)
textplot_wordcloud(fr_dfm, comparison = TRUE, color = c("darkgreen", "red"))

The comparison word cloud highlights many of the differences that are observable from the separate word clouds above. However, this word cloud makes it clear that the Fresh reviews are more likely to contain positive words like âgreat,â âbest,â âoriginal,â âfun,â âentertaining,â and âclassicâ than Rotten reviews are. Rotten reviews are more likely to contain negative words like âbadâ and ânothingâ along with words about largely negatively-received series such as âTwilight,â âUnderworld,â âBlade,â and the word âfranchiseâ in general.

Co-Occurrence Networks

I was curious to see if the ways in which critics described vampires in their reviews would be indicative of their feelings about the movies. In order to do so, I created co-occurrence networks to examine the 30 most frequent words that were 5 words or fewer away from the words âvampireâ or âvampires.â

# tokenize corpora; remove punctuation, numbers, and stopwords
fresh_tokens <- tokens(fresh_corpus, remove_punct = T, remove_numbers = T) |>
  tokens_select(pattern = stopwords(), select = "remove") |> tokens_tolower()
rotten_tokens <- tokens(rotten_corpus, remove_punct = T, remove_numbers = T) |>
  tokens_select(pattern = stopwords(), select = "remove") |> tokens_tolower()
# keep words surrounding "vampire" or "vampires" in reviews
fresh_near_vamp <- tokens_select(fresh_tokens, pattern = "vampire",
                                 window = 5, selection = "keep")
fresh_near_vamps <- tokens_select(fresh_tokens, pattern = "vampires",
                                  window = 5, selection = "keep")
rotten_near_vamp <- tokens_select(rotten_tokens, pattern = "vampire",
                                  window = 5, selection = "keep")
rotten_near_vamps <- tokens_select(rotten_tokens, pattern = "vampires",
                                   window = 5, selection = "keep")

# create feature co-occurrence matrices
fresh_fcm1 <- fcm(fresh_near_vamp, context = "window")
fresh_fcm2 <- fcm(fresh_near_vamps, context = "window")
rotten_fcm1 <- fcm(rotten_near_vamp, context = "window")
rotten_fcm2 <- fcm(rotten_near_vamps, context = "window")

# only keep 30 most frequent co-occurring words
top_fresh_feats1 <- names(sort(colSums(fresh_fcm1), decreasing = TRUE)[1:30]) 
vamp_fresh_fcm <- fcm_select(fresh_fcm1, pattern = c("vampire", top_fresh_feats1))
top_fresh_feats2 <- names(sort(colSums(fresh_fcm2), decreasing = TRUE)[1:30]) 
vamps_fresh_fcm <- fcm_select(fresh_fcm2, pattern = c("vampires", top_fresh_feats2))
top_rot_feats1 <- names(sort(colSums(rotten_fcm1), decreasing = TRUE)[1:30]) 
vamp_rot_fcm <- fcm_select(rotten_fcm1, pattern = c("vampire", top_rot_feats1))
top_rot_feats2 <- names(sort(colSums(rotten_fcm2), decreasing = TRUE)[1:30]) 
vamps_rot_fcm <- fcm_select(rotten_fcm2, pattern = c("vampires", top_rot_feats2))
set.seed(12)
textplot_network(vamp_fresh_fcm)
set.seed(12)
textplot_network(vamps_fresh_fcm)

The co-occurrence networks of âvampireâ and âvampiresâ for Fresh reviews include some positive words such as âoriginal,â âlove,â âbest,â and ânew.â There are also some words like âIranian,â âSwedish,â âAbraham,â âLincoln,â âTwilight,â and âJarmuschâ which are specific to certain movies.

set.seed(12)
textplot_network(vamp_rot_fcm)
set.seed(12)
textplot_network(vamps_rot_fcm)

The co-occurrence networks of âvampireâ and âvampiresâ for Rotten reviews include some negative words like âbad,â âdull,â and âsuck,â but they also feature some positive words like âgood,â âbetter,â âfun,â and âright.â Similarly to the co-occurrence networks for the positive reviews, there are some movie-specific words such as âAbraham,â âLincoln,â âAcademy,â âTwilight,â and âUnderworld.â

Supervised Learning

With a basic understanding of some of the most common words used in positive and negative reviews of vampire movies, I proceeded to apply supervised learning techniques to the data. My goal was to see how well these algorithms could predict the sentiment of the reviews and which words in the reviews were most strongly used to signal the sentiment.

# make one big corpus
vamp_reviews$review_ID <- seq(1:nrow(vamp_reviews))
vamp_corpus <- corpus(vamp_reviews, docid_field = "review_ID",
                      text_field = "review_content")
docvars(vamp_corpus, "review_ID") <- vamp_reviews$review_ID
ndoc(vamp_corpus)
[1] 8254
# set seed, then split into training and testing sets
set.seed(12)
N <- ndoc(vamp_corpus)
trainIndex <- sample(1:N, .8*N)
testIndex <- c(1:N)[-trainIndex]

# create dfms for different subsets
dfmTrain <- corpus_subset(vamp_corpus, review_ID %in% trainIndex) |>
  tokens() |> dfm() |> dfm_trim(min_docfreq = 20)
dim(dfmTrain) # 80% of all documents
[1] 6603  856
dfmTest <- corpus_subset(vamp_corpus, review_ID %in% testIndex) |>
  tokens() |> dfm()
dim(dfmTest) # 20% of all documents
[1] 1651 6759

Naive Bayes Model

# run Naive Bayes model on the training data
nb_model <- textmodel_nb(dfmTrain, docvars(dfmTrain, "review_freshness"),
                         distribution = "Bernoulli")

Topic Modeling

In addition to building ML models, I wanted to see which topics could be extracted from the reviews.

# add new column to dataframe with sentiment as binary numeric variable
vamp_reviews <- vamp_reviews |>
  mutate(review_freshness01 = ifelse(review_freshness=="Fresh", 1, 0))

# create DFM using all reviews and all features
dfmAll <- tokens(vamp_reviews$review_content, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE) |> 
  dfm() |> dfm_remove(stopwords('english'))
dim(dfmAll)
[1]  8254 16264
# build structural topic model with 5 topics
vamp_stm <- stm(dfmAll, K = 5, data = vamp_reviews,
               prevalence = ~ review_freshness01,
               max.em.its = 500, seed = 12,
               init.type = "Spectral", verbose = FALSE)
# visualize the 5 topics
plot(vamp_stm, type="summary")
# examine top words that define each topic
labelTopics(vamp_stm)

None of these topics seem particularly easy to interpret. The first topic seems to contain generic words about movies, without any highly positive or negative words. The second, third, and fourth topics seem more positive, since they contain words like âfilm,â âgenre,â âhorror,â âfun,â and âbest,â which have previously been shown to be associated more with well-reviewed movies. The last topic seems most directly related to vampires, with words like âvampire,â âaction,â and âhorrorâ among the top words.

# name topics using top 3 words in "score" category from each topic
topicNames <- labelTopics(vamp_stm, n=3)$score
topicLabels <- rep(NA, 5)
for (i in 1:5){
  topicLabels[i] <- paste(topicNames[i,], collapse = "_")
}
topicLabels
[1] "movie_can_movies"        "film_one_genre"         
[3] "never_fun_horror"        "just_best_even"         
[5] "vampire_action_original"
# estimate and plot effects of review freshness on topics
modelEffects <- estimateEffect(formula = 1:5 ~ review_freshness01,
                               stmobj = vamp_stm,
                               metadata = vamp_reviews)
par(mfrow = c(2, 3), bty = "n", lwd = 2)
for (i in 1:5){
  plot.estimateEffect(modelEffects,
                      covariate = "review_freshness01",
                      xlim = c(-.1, .1),
                      model = vamp_stm,
                      topics = modelEffects$topics[i],
                      method = "difference",
                      cov.value1 = 1,
                      cov.value2 = 0, 
                      main = topicLabels[i],
                      printlegend = F,
                      verbose.labels = F)
  par(new = F)
}

The plots of the effects of the sentiment of the reviews on the topics reveal that none of the effects are particularly large. Topic 1 has the most negative association with sentiment, and Topic 5 has the most positive association with sentiment, but both of those effects are around 0.05, and the other topics have effects that are even closer to 0. This topic model didnât contribute much of any useful information to my findings, so I might have to alter my DFM that I used to build the STM in the first place to get more interesting results, if I want to use topic modeling at all.

Conclusions

Out of the three supervised learning models that I applied to my data, the Naive Bayes model performed the best, with a classification accuracy of 70%. The Random Forest and Support Vector Machine models were close behind, with accuracies of 68% and 67%, respectively. Since all of these results were obtained using only one training and testing set of data, I need to rerun all of these models on different random subsets of the data to see whether I get similar results. I could also develop an ensemble model, giving equal weight to the Naive Bayes, Random Forest, and SVM models, since they all performed relatively equally, to see if those predictions would be at all improved over those from the individual models.

Throughout my analysis, I have repeatedly come across the issue of the high weight that is given to words about specific vampire movies that are almost exclusively positively or negatively reviewed. For example, words that are associated with A Girl Walks Home Alone at Night, directed by Ana Lily Amirpour (including âIranianâ and âAmirpourâ), Only Lovers Left Alive, directed by Jim Jarmusch (including âJarmuschâ and âJarmuschâsâ), and What We Do in the Shadows, directed by Taika Waititi and Jemaine Clement (including âshadowsâ and âmockumentaryâ), are repeatedly featured in the positive word analyses. Likewise, words that are associated with the Twilight, Underworld, and Blade series are repeatedly featured in the negative word analyses. I considered removing references to specific movie titles, characters, or creative personnel from my corpora, but that may have led to a loss of information in reviews that refer to these other movies in a positive or negative comparative way.

Overall, I saw evidence to support both of my initial hypotheses. Fresh reviews of vampire movies frequently included words such as âgood,â âgreat,â âbest,â âfun,â âoriginal,â âlove,â âentertaining,â âclassic,â and âpleasure.â Rotten reviews of vampire movies frequently included words such as âbad,â âdull,â âpoor,â âboring,â âworst,â ânothing,â âmess,â âtedious,â and âflat.â These results align with what I expected to see from my first hypothesis. Additionally, the word âhorrorâ was repeatedly associated more with Fresh reviews than Rotten reviews, which aligns with my second hypothesis.

In the future, I would like to apply my supervised learning models to reviews of newer vampire movies on Rotten Tomatoes that were published after 2020 and thus werenât included in my dataset. I would be curious to see how well the models would perform on this new data to determine whether the results Iâve observed so far could be considered generalizable or not.
